# Building a Public Health Data Agent: Module 0: Setting Up Your Environment

## Introduction

As a product data scientist I’m excited about the new possibilities that generative AI, and particularly agent-based systems, provide. I enjoy helping various stakeholders understand our business through data, but I don’t enjoy the interrupts and urgent requests to answer descriptive questions. I would love to offload some of these requests to an LLM-based system that allows non-technical users self-service their data questions, so I thought I would attempt to build something that fits the bill.

I will use Google's [ADK Framework](https://google.github.io/adk-docs/) and integrate the agent with a number of BigQuery tables in Google Cloud. As a dataset I have chosen the [CDC’s National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey](https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/index.html) (NHANES), a dataset with detailed health information about 10,000s of Americans stretching over a decade from 1999 to 2018\. When this project is finished the data agent should use this data to answer end user users questions like:

* "Compare activity levels between different states”?  
* “How have obesity rates for male teenagers changed between 2000 and 2018”?  
* “Is Vitamin D intake associated with sleep duration for adults over 40?”

 To make this work more achievable I have split it into modules:

0. **Setup:** Creating a Google Cloud Project, Uploading the  NHANES data to this project, setting up a VSCode project that can access Google Cloud, uploading the project to GitHub  
1. **Initial Data Exploration:** Exploring the NHANES data in a Jupyter notebook)  
2. The Query Agent: Building a simple agent that can execute queries based on natural language prompts and giving it the context to effectively query the NHANES data)  
3. **The Visualization Agent:** Adding a bespoke python-powered visualization agent to the multi-agent system)  
4. **The Analyst Agent:** Adding a specialized BigQuery ML agent to the multi-agent system  
5. **Deployment and Productianization:** Deploy the whole system to Cloud Run so that end-users can interact with the agents to draw lessons from the NHANES data

For each module I will provide a step-by-step guide so that you can create something similar, starting with the Setup Module, below.

## Setting Up An Environment for a Google Cloud AI Project

### Creating and preparing the Google Cloud Project

1. Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/) and create a new project. I labelled mine \`Public Health Agent’.

![][image1]

2. Activate the Vertex AI API and the BigQuery API. The easiest way to do this is to navigate to the Vertex AI landing page in your new project. It will prompt you to enable a bunch of APIs relevant for data science and AI projects.

### Creating and preparing a VSCode project

1. If you haven’t done so already, download and install [VS Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/).  
2. If you haven’t done so already, create a [GitHub account](https://github.com/) and download GitHub Desktop.  
3. In VS Code, create a new python project, I called mine \`\`  
   1. Create a folder called ‘0\_data\_preparation’  
4. Install the following extensions  
   1. Google Cloud Code  
   2. Gemini Code Assist  
   3. Jupyter  
   4. Python  
5. Restart VS Code as an administrator and run the following commands in the terminal:  
   1. `Set-ExecutionPolicy -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Scope CurrentUser`  
   2. `gcloud auth application-default login`

   this authentication will later allow you to access your google cloud project from this virtual environment.

### Uploading the NHANES data to google cloud

1. Next we need to upload the NHANES dataset into BigQuery in your Google Cloud Project. This is a little bit tricky, because the NHANES datafiles are in the XPT data format, which bigquery doesn’t recognize, so we must convert them into CSVs before we can upload them.  
2. I wrote a script (with the help of Gemini) to download all the files, convert them, and upload them into BigQuery. You can find them in the data preparation folder in [this GitHub repository](https://github.com/Sjnjerak/GCP-Public-Health-Data-Agent/tree/main).  
3. Simply run `python 0_data_preparation/run_pipeline.py` in a bash terminal in your VS Code project and if you have authenticated correctly and have labelled your project the same thing I labelled mine all of the data should automatically be uploaded to BigQuery.

### Creating a Jupyter Notebook that can interact with the BQ data and can be run from the VS Console

1. Create a new folder called `1_Exploring_CDC_NHANES_in_colab`  
2. Use the Jupyter Notebook extension to create a Jupyter Notebook in this folder, label it something like \`Public\_Health\_Agent\_Notebook.ipynb\`  
3. Use pip to install Pandas and BigQuery in your virtual notebook environment.  
4. Add a cell to enable BigQuery magic in your notebook and link it to your project, it should look something like this:

\# Step 1: Load the BigQuery magic extension.  
\# You only need to run this once per notebook session.  
%load\_ext bigquery\_magics

\# Step 2: Set your default project ID (optional but recommended).  
\# The magic will use the project from your gcloud config, but setting it  
\# here makes your notebook's dependencies clear.  
\# Replace 'your-gcp-project-id' with your actual project ID.  
%env GCLOUD\_PROJECT\=public\-health\-agent

5. Check that you can query the NHANES data from inside your notebook. If you have labelled your project the same way as mine and used my code to upload the data, it should look something like this:

%%bigquery

SELECT  
  \*  
FROM  
  \`public\-health\-agent.nhanes\_data.DEMO\_1999\_2000\`  
LIMIT 10;

6. Push all of your edits to your GitHub repository.

Congratulations\! You have now set up a new Google Cloud Project, uploaded the NHANES data to that project, and linked that project to a VS code environment. In the next module we will use BigQuery and Python to explore some of this data. We will use the work from the next module to train our agent later, and to assess how well it is doing.
